{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6eb2e036-8462-4acc-ba74-b136c351f8f8","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/   ← user-level crashes\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/    ← system-level crashes\n```\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**Quick way to find it:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\n**You can also use Console.app** → select \"Crash Reports\" in the sidebar.\n\nThese `.ips` files contain the native backtrace, signal info (e.g., `EXC_BAD_ACCESS`), and register state. If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames in the crash log, I can help with that too — just share the `.ips` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ae1f865-7040-434d-ab9b-c1fc5d650a1f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question about macOS crash reporting - I can answer directly.","outputTokens":303,"requestId":"7847:1E23BC:47BAF5:5343F2:69FA9DC0"},"id":"f97e6a28-e288-4287-bb96-236504e2a5b7","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:47:53.375Z","parentId":"8532aed5-1601-4e5b-9566-06a7567137ab"}
